{With no 4-card Major suit you respond 2\D to partner's Stayman bid. Partner now bids 2NT.  

With no 4-card Major suit you respond 2\D to partner's Stayman bid. Partner now bids 2NT. 

With 17 points you naturally accept partner's invitation and bid 3NT.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \HQ.

East's \HQ lead presents you with an immediate decision (or two) to make.

Winner List: \S = 2 : \H = 2 : \D = 0 : \C = 1 :: Total = 5

You need 4 additional winners and can only establish 3 of them in \Ds. So you will have to manufacture another one from the \C suit as well. If you assume the \C finesse will fail, (and you have probably noticed that most finesses <b>DO</b> fail on these pages), that means you will lose the lead twice.

So what do you do about that \HQ? Do you win or hold up? 

You hold up, of course, to cut defensive communications when East has 5 \Hs and West has 3. East will probably play another \H to dummy's \HK. 

If both the \DA and \CK are in East's hand then you won't make this contract. He will easily establish his \Hs and have an entry to get in and cash them. If the \DA is with East and the \CK is with West then it doesn't matter in which order you play the suits since you will not lose the lead in \Cs. But if the \CK is with East and the \DA is with West then it is vital that you play \Cs first.

If you play on \Ds first, West will win the \DA and play his last \H, forcing out your \HA. When East wins his \CK he will cash 2 more \Hs.

But, if you finesse in \Cs first, East can win and establish the \H suit. But, when West wins the \DA, he will have no \H to return.}
[Play "W"]HQ

